  1. Checking for linearity
par( mfrow = c(3,2) )
plot(df$case,residuals(model))
plot(df$Taxes,residuals(model))
plot(df$Size,residuals(model))
plot(df$New,residuals(model))
plot(df$Baths,residuals(model))
plot(df$Beds,residuals(model))

Case, Taxes and Size have plots which are random which implies linearity. We shall check plots of studentized residuals vs covariates.

par( mfrow = c(3,2) )
plot(df$case,rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)
plot(df$Taxes,rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)
plot(df$Size,rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)
plot(df$New,rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)
plot(df$Baths,rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)
plot(df$Beds,rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)

From the plots we can see that case follows some kind of pattern. Size and taxes are random with a few outliers. We shall check plots of residuals vs fitted values.

par(mfrow= c(1,2))
plot(fitted(model),residuals(model))
plot(fitted(model),rstudent(model))
abline(2,0)
abline(-2,0)

Since there is no pattern in both the plots we can say the variables are linear even though we have some outliers in our rstudent plot.

From the above plot we can see that variance is not constant throughout. As covariates are increasing, the variance in Y is increasing

Normaility Assumption check. We plot the Quantile Quantile plot to check normality.

qqnorm(residuals(model))

Ideally we would like the dots to be evenly spaced or closely evenly spaaced. But we can see that this is a heavy tailed, which may indicate that it is not normal.

We do not need to check Independence Assumption as we do not have any time variable. For example, We are not checking how the price of a house is affected with time. What was the price in 2010 and what is the price now. If that was the case we would have had to check the independence assumption. For this particular example we assume that the assumption in met.

library(MASS)
